Terentius Varro Murena was by adoption a brother of Terentia, the wife of Maecenas, who incurred Augustus’s displeasure by divulging to her the secret of the dis- covered conspiracy (Suet. Any. 66). He was the Licinius Murena to whom Horace addressed the famous ode on the Golden Mean (Carm. ΙΙ. 10); in 23 Bc. he was Augustus’s colleague in the consulship, but within a year he was involved in the conspiracy with Fannius Caepio. Cf. Suet. Tib. S; Vell. Patere. 11.91; Dio, LIV. 3. —Egnatiusz M. Egnatius Rufus. by his demagogical and arrogant conduct, rendered himself offensive to Augustus and was prevented from standing for the consulship. After his con- spiracy against the emperor he met his death in prison. Cf. Vell. Patere. II. 91—92; Dio, LIII. 24; Tac. Ann.
